320","1295–1327":"1295–1327","1297–Male":"1297–Deceased","1299–Male":"1299–Deceased","1292–1349":"1292–1349","1320–1370":"1320–1370","1260–1355":"1260–1355","1266–1360":"1266–1360","1297":"1297","1295":"1295","1360":"1360","1260":"1260","1370":"1370","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1289":"1289","1355":"1355","Abt 1320":"about 1320","1266":"1266","1299":"1299","1320":"1320","1317":"1317","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Wrenbury, Cheshire, England":"Wrenbury, Cheshire, England","Northwich, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northwich, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Aldersely","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name possibly, in the form  <i>Alderleys</i>, from a lost medieval settlement in Allerton near Bradford (WR Yorks) later recorded as  <i>Aldersley</i> with a transitional form seen in 1545, and perhaps first found in the compound name  <i>Aldeleysike</i> in 1292. It is not always distinguishable from   Alderley   in (2).","2  English: occasionally perhaps a variant of   Alderley  , but the relationship may be the other way round."],"variants":[{"name":"Alderley","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Alderley (Cheshire), which is recorded as  <i>Aldredelie</i> in 1086,  <i>Aldridelegh</i> in 1290.","2  English: occasionally perhaps a variant of   Aldersley  , but the relationship may be the other way round."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and per